<title type="html"><![CDATA[Recommended cpu architecture and platform for beginners?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4895&amp;p=43699#p43699"><![CDATA[
i would suggest you learn the asm for what ever you are programming.  if you are writing nes emulator or game, then i would suggest 6502.<br /><br />if you are writing an application to run on an x86 cpu, then i would suggest learning x86.   you can use gcc -S with c source code to show the asm <br /><br />i would not waste my time learning DOS or bios interrupt calls, those are deprecated and have no modern use.   (might i ask why you want to learn bios routines ?    i dont think windows or linux uses those at all, and i think bsd might still use 1)<br /><br />not sure i can suggest what to learn.  depends what you want to do with it.   i would suggest 6502, x86, or arm.<br /><br />matt<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=170">mattmatteh</a> — Wed Feb 25, 2009 12:59 pm</p><hr />
