<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4895&amp;p=43696#p43696"><![CDATA[
I'm sort of a noob here, but I do have experience with x86 assembly language. I taught myself years ago with a book by Jeff Duntemann called "Assembly Language: Step by Step." That book was a godsend. It is one of the clearest and most enjoyable programming books I've ever read. If you can get your hands on that book, and TASM or MASM, and use it on a computer with DOS (or use DosBox perhaps), I would highly recommend that. <br /><br />*edit*<br /><br />Here is the book on amazon. I have the old copy with the black cover, but this version covers doing assembly programming on linux as well as dos (same book though so I'm sure still great):<br /><br /><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Assembly-Language-Step-step-Programming/dp/0471375233/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1235589776&amp;sr=8-2" class="postlink">http://www.amazon.com/Assembly-Language-Step-step-Programming/dp/0471375233/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1235589776&amp;sr=8-2</a><br /><br /><br />I haven't been doing nesdev long, but I can definitely say my prior x86 experience has made it relatively easy for me to learn some of the basics. Good luck!<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3735">GradualGames</a> — Wed Feb 25, 2009 12:06 pm</p><hr />
